rn Staff</a> <br /><a href="HTTP://ffxiv.zam.com/db/item.html?ffxivitem=5020114" rel="external nofollow" title="ffxiv.zam.com/db/item.html?ffxivitem=5020114">Brand</a> <br /><a href="HTTP://ffxiv.zam.com/db/item.html?ffxivitem=5020202" rel="external nofollow" title="ffxiv.zam.com/db/item.html?ffxivitem=5020202">Wind Brand</a> <br /><a href="HTTP://ffxiv.zam.com/db/item.html?ffxivitem=5020203" rel="external nofollow" title="ffxiv.zam.com/db/item.html?ffxivitem=5020203">Earth Brand</a> <br /><a href="HTTP://ffxiv.zam.com/db/item.html?ffxivitem=5020204" rel="external nofollow" title="ffxiv.zam.com/db/item.html?ffxivitem=5020204">lightning Brand</a> <br /><a href="HTTP://ffxiv.zam.com/db/item.html?ffxivitem=5020205" rel="external nofollow" title="ffxiv.zam.com/db/item.html?ffxivitem=5020205">Ice Brand</a> <br /><a href="HTTP://ffxiv.zam.com/db/item.html?ffxivitem=5020206" rel="external nofollow" title="ffxiv.zam.com/db/item.html?ffxivitem=5020206">Fire Brand</a> <br /><a href="HTTP://ffxiv.zam.com/db/item.html?ffxivitem=5020207" rel="external nofollow" title="ffxiv.zam.com/db/item.html?ffxivitem=5020207">Water Brand</a> <br /><a href="HTTP://ffxiv.zam.com/db/item.html?ffxivitem=5020208" rel="external nofollow" title="ffxiv.zam.com/db/item.html?ffxivitem=5020208">Brass Cudgel</a> <br /><a href="HTTP://ffxiv.zam.com/db/item.html?ffxivitem=5020302" rel="external nofollow" title="ffxiv.zam.com/db/item.html?ffxivitem=5020302">Iron Cudgel</a> <br />---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- <br /> <br /> <br />---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- <br /> <br />4. <b>Spell Combinations:</b> <br />Action combinations that work well for THM: <br />e.g. PD/Damnation/Slow/Dia/Banish/Poison/Cure/Sacrifice/Siphon MP/Pun. Barbs/Shock Spikes <br />-this combo uses up most of your action points but I found great for solo at Rank 22. <br />You will notice I have added CONJUROR spells there. These are pretty useful for a solo THM. Its definately worth leveling CON up for Cure and Shock Spikes. Stoneskin good also, as is protect and Shell. CON and THM spells stack nicely together but just dont forget that other class actions have penalties as in slower cast and recast times. Stoneskin as a THM seems to take a long time!  <br /> <br />The Conjuror ability <a href="HTTP://ffxiv.zam.com/en/ability.html?ffxivability=29479" rel="external nofollow" title="ffxiv.zam.com/en/ability.html?ffxivability=29479">Fastcast</a> is a very useful trait that you can purchase with Conjuror guildmarks. Levelling up your CON for this ability seems very well worth it. An example of why this is a good idea is when you are ‘competing’ with another mage for SP, Fastcast gives you the distinct advantage. I was doing this the other day with another THM (Hey Taedium! :)), who had fastcast. Every time we both began to heal I would end up second. I still received a very good amount of SP but as I came second best each time I realised that we all should get this trait. I have urgently started ranking up my CON because of this. In addition to this having a R20 CON helps us out as we get Cure II which can’t be a bad thing either :) <br /> <br />Party Spell Combo's <br />Recently I have been trying our several debuffs etc. At 29 here is my list of spells set: <br />Top row: <br />PD/Silouette/Damnation/Scourge/ABS ACC/Profundity/Poison/Paralyze <br />Second row: <br />Sacrifice I&amp;II/CureI&amp;II/Siphon MP/Stygian Spikes/Punishing Barbs/Protect/Shell/Exaltation <br /> <br />Good ideas anyone?  <br />Scourge/Bio/Blood Rite and Damnation? <br />Banish/Dia/Blood Rite/Dark Seal and Damnation? <br />Gravity/poison/bio/Dia - DoT kills? <br />---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- <br /> <br />7. <b>Solo Hunting Grounds</b> -  <br />You can solo as a THM, in fact using our abilities many classes benefit from greater survivability when soloing. I recommend soloing from at least 1-10 as you will learn aspects of the job and these ranks are you initial training exercise. 10-20 you can solo with no massive difficulties but after about rank 15 you may want to start picking up your first party. The reason for this, simple you will start getting more SP, and you will find it more difficult to get maximum SP from a single mob but more importantly you will need to learn how to play the job with others around. Even though at the time of writing there is no end-game content in the game, there will be and I guess that, like other classes, THM will have its role to play. Post 20 I have found THM a difficult job to solo, not because we can’t beat mobs, but because the way we get SP is by casting and the solo caster is at present in no way rewarded for this. <br />The solo guides below are what I’ve found on my travels of various versions of the game (alpha to Beta to retail) But first you may want to try these links from other people in ZAM: <br /><a href="http://ffxiv.zam.com/wiki/FFXIV_Leveling_Guide" title="http://ffxiv.zam.com/wiki/FFXIV_Leveling_Guide" rel="external nofollow">http://ffxiv.zam.com/wiki/FFXIV_Leveling_Guide</a> <br /><a href="http://ffxiv.zam.com/forum.html?game=268&amp;mid=1286831975150948549&amp;page=1" title="http://ffxiv.zam.com/forum.html?game=268&amp;mid=1286831975150948549&amp;page=1" rel="external">http://ffxiv.zam.com/forum.html?game=268&amp;mid=1286831975150948549&amp;page=1</a> <br />Both links are good but I have added a few of my own personal spots in the information below... <br /> <br />a)<span style="color:red">La Noscea</span> <br />(Rank 1 -2): <br /><i>Wharf Rats</i>: These are plentiful around Camp Bearded Rock and even further afield. Around level 5 or so they get a little too easy and you get less rank points. <br />(Rank 4-5): <i>Lost Wethers</i> and <i>Lost Ewes</i> - bottom right of the map near the 'Treasures of the Main' quest. This area has many mobs and is hardly used by other players. (<i>many thanks to Chrysothemis for info!</i>) **Open Beta update*** Sheep in limsa are still good for soloing. However, salamanders now aggro and the closest aetheryte node is blocked by salamanders, so you have to walk all the way back from Bearded Rock if you die. There is also a gobbue that aggros in the area, but it's not hard to avoid. Sheep also drop a lot of wind shards, which if you are a crafter from Ul'dah, you might need, as they are hard to find in Thanalan. <br />(Rank 7 - 8): <br />Difficult to find anything that really gave me good exp - You can try <i>Puks</i> if you can find easy prey ones - they give really good exp even at 9 but are tough to kill and you'll need to replentish mp a lot. <i>Aeriela</i> (Jellyfish) are a little easier and give similar rank points. These can be found near the coastal regions of the area around Camp Bearded Rock. <br /> <br />(Rank 9 - 11): <br /><i>Fireflies</i> - <s>These are very easy to kill, but are impervious (as far as I can tell) to magical attacks. SO the way to kill is Phantom Dart, damnation and then sacrifice Heal. These mobs are camped quite often though so you may be competing for them. Luckily unless another mage or archer is around you can usually engage the mob more quickly than any other mele class (that I came across anyway). The Fireflies I fought were in a cave at the far North-Western tip past Camp Bearded Rock but I have seen them in other caves also.</s> Went to try this out in retail and unfortunately the exp gained by fighting these mobs has been seriously nerfed :(. Was only getting normal exp (0-250) - for blue --&gt; red mobs. Still these mobs are not too risky to kill and drop fire shards if you need. <br /> <br />(levels 11-14): <br />After what seemed like an age (I did a few Levequests at Skull Valley camp) I found a very nice spot just north of the camp – so for those of you complaining about running to the aetherlyte all the time its right there! <br />Vs. <i>Roseling</i> – These can be tough but a decent THM can take them on. Just watch out for their detection range as it seems very far. <br />Mainly used Phantom Dart and Damnation with the Debuffs etc thrown in. You can easily go three to four mobs without getting mp drained – even more if you are good! I found one nice trick – don’t get too far away from them as their range attack hits for lots of dmg – move in close and preferably with your back to a wall (because they have a force back move). After a while I was getting very decent rank points (200-400) per kill. <br /> <br />(Levels 14+) <br />Mot done much yet but <i>Aldgoat Nanny</i> if you can beat them (and I did) can yield up to 500 Rank points per kill! <br />Try <i>Phorosfly’s</i> in the cave between Bloodshore and Cederwood zones. These are the Firefly’s older cousins but just as easy and decent rank points. <br /> <i>Bloodshore Bell</i> – Jellyfish and lots of them are north of Bloodshore camp. They don’t agro or link and as long as your def is good they can be taken down easily with PD+Damnation and Sacrifice. Seem immune to most other magic though.***Usually overcamped*** <br />***New Camp*** - Very good but needs a certain technique <br /><i> Moraby Mole</i> – These things hit hard At level 15 so be careful. I found a great camp thats perfect for this technique at 32 – 22/23 past the tunnel near Camp Bloodshore. Its a little circle between two areas and full of Mole’s  - plenty to kill. The technique I found was to use the following spells only &gt;&gt; PD&gt;Damnation&gt;Sacrifice. Build up your tp and use Damnation a lot because you’ll need to maintain your mp levels. Keep an eye on your hp – dont let it get into red. The moles will always do a range attack which hits for a lot first and then move in where they hit for a little less. The ‘technique’ though is for when they do their disappear and reappear move as this can hit for 275+ and can make things quite nasty. The zone that you are fighting these mobs in allows you to run out of their spawn range quite easily so you can avoid this move – sacrifice  - and move back for the kill. I leveled very quickly in what is I think a dry period for leveling [see above].  <br />(Levels 18-22) Still killing Bloodshore Bell's, however they are starting to run a little low on Rank points.... 49-259 for the last 2k at rank 18 - I may need new hunting grounds! <br />The swarm/mole/roseling camp past the tunnels near Bloodshore was good for a few k if you can take the generally low rank points :( <br />Casseopia Hollow <br /><i>Casseopia</i>’s can give decent exp – I found that if I could stand the grind its a good spot next to the Aetherlite Crystal – watch out for the Sea Hares on the way down though, they can one-shot you [not confirmed but I think this has been fixed now]. I found opening with Slow&gt;Scourge&gt;PD until Damnation gets you quite far with Sacrifice thrown in for good measure. <br />*** There are 4 Bombs/lightning Elementals  to the far west inside the Hollow . As a 22 THM I was able to take them down for extremely good and fast Rank points<s> (250-934) </s> . The Elementals give the most rank points but can be easier than the bombs which can be tricky as they hit faster. All mobs here cast Tier II magic so be very aware of this. I did die a lot here but the exp was so good it was worth it. Also worth noting that it appears that if you don't have buffs on and dont use magic attack spellsyou get more rank points. ***  <br /> <br />b) <span style="color:red">Thanalan</span> <br /> <br />Rank 1-8: Solo the Star Marmots, Copper Coblyns around Camp Blackbeard. Heading north of the camp yeilds quite a few mobs that are not being camped too much at the minute although these areas are becoming more popular. At these levels quick kills = quick ranking up - dont aim for anything higher. Around the east of Ul'dah is a small valley where I found quite a lot of mobs (Including beetles which can be nice rank points). Head out of the east gate and head south east from then on - its not far at all.  <br /> <br />Rank 8-10: Found this a very difficult level to rank up because you are not high enough for Dodo's yet. I went around Camp drybone and headed to the west of the map (near where you do the Yarzon leves) and fought coblyns and marmots again (Thistletails). If you look on you map in this area you will see some cave systems (shaped sort of like stars), inside here I found a bountiful supply of marmots. <br />7/8-10 A cave with two parts at 36/26-27 (the one just southwest of Camp Drybone) AWESOME xp - (credit to RhysOnKujata)  <br /> <br />10-13 I went to a cave at 39/18 (northeast of the golden bazaar on the same level as it is, you have to run through there to get to it.) Using both of these combined with the 2/3-7 spot of 22/29 allowed me to rush 3 different ranks to 12 in about 4 hours of nothing but grind time. <br />Rank 10-14: Dodo's - these are tough at 10 so be careful. Set slow and keep healing yourself as often as possible. At 11 you can just about manage the balance of dmg vs mp by using exaltation as often as the timer is up. Once you hit 12+ these are not too much of a problem and you can forgo the buffs/debuffs so save mp etc. Dodo's can give you up to 400+ rank points per kill and the fights can last a long time. I killed what was in the region while I was waiting for them to spawn. Honestly wasnt as slow as I thought it was going to be. <br />10-13 I went to a cave at 39/18 (northeast of the golden bazaar on the same level as it is, you have to run through there to get to it.) Using both of these combined with the 2/3-7 spot of 22/29 allowed me to rush 3 different ranks to 12 in about 4 hours of nothing but grind time.(credit to RhysOnKujata)  <br /> <br />Rank 14+: Ok at this point I am rank 16 and I have been working my way around camp horizon. The aldgoats here are red and too tough to fight but there are a few dodo's and lots of marmots here. I just circle around a wide area to find things to kill. I know this is a solo guide but if you can duo with a mele class (PUG very good) you can get fantastic skill ups vs the aldgoats. Just keep yourself on the opposite side of the goat of your teamate so when the goat uses the knockback move you can sacrifice while running forward to him to keep him alove. <br /> <br />Please add anything in the thread that you feel will help others and I will update. <br /> <br />c) <span style="color:red">Near Gridania</span> <br /> <br />TBA – Sorry as my character was created in Ul’Dah (previously in Limsa Lominsa) – I have never tried to solo in this area at any great length. There appears to be lots of low level marmots and various other mobs and looks like there is a quite a rich source of mobs, moving to the upper canopies when you reach R10+. (If anyone has any further information for this I would be very grateful) <br />---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- <br /> <br />---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- <br /> <br />8. <b>STATS</b> <br /> <br />If you are a mage and plan to solo at all it is thoughtful that you put some of your points into VIT and get gear that gives you more DEF. I have recently been doing this and it makes a big difference to your survivability. After recent testing I have concluded that for Phantom Dart (at least) added STR <u>does not</u> increase damage. The only stat I would definately raise is VIT to help with your survivability. <br /> <br /><b> The current thinking about stats is that although they seem broken THM benefit most by raising MND&gt;VIT&gt;PIE - Many players are still testing this but Your VIT,MND and PIE <i>should</i> be considerably more than any other stat. MND will give you a much larger MP pool which is not a bad thing but also let you Cure/Sacrifice people for more HP. VIT will increase your survivability greatly as it will raise your HP and also mitigate some damage done by mobs by inadvertantly raising your DEF.PIE will help your debuffs stick and seems to increase damage on our nukes. INT does not seem to play much of a role for a THM at the minute believe it or not. INT is better used by CON's to raise the damage of their nukes. You should not raise this by much if at all</b> <br /> <br />---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- <br /> <br />9. <span style="color:purple">MACRO'S</span> <br /> <br />Going to improve this section very soon but just for now I'll add two important ones that I've found very useful. Each have a separate binding for: <br /> <br />/aoe on <br />/aoe off <br /> <br />These are great in party situations so your THM can quickly switch from party heal, single target heal and aoe  debuffs when no other mobs are around. <br /> <br />There are two ways of selecting your spells, one is through the keyboard numbers 1 through 10 (0) then hitting enter to cast the spell and the other is through macro's. So a macro for Aoe Scourge would look like this:  <br /> <br />/aoe on  <br />/action &quot;Scourge&quot; main &lt;t&gt;  <br /> <br />and obviously 'off' for single target  <br /> <br />*** When you use this method you do not have to hit enter, you do not see a green icon or a purple circle. *** <br /> <br />My recommendation (and this is personal preference but I feel it orders me well) is that your macro’s use the first two rows, CTRL being your main Cures (1-4 set for Sacrifice I, Cure I, Sacrifice II and Cure II) and ALT being for your buffs/debuffs such as Punishing Barbs, Exhaltation etc. Here is how mine are currently layed out: <br /> <br />CTRL+1     = Sacrifice <br />CTRL+2     = Cure  <br />CTRL+3     = Sacrifice II <br />CTRL+4     = Cure II <br />CTRL+5     = Protect and Shell <br />CTRL+6-0   not used as of yet. <br />ALT+1     = Aoe off <br />ALT+2     = Aoe On <br />ALT+3     = Exaltation <br />ALT+4     = Stoneskin <br />ALT+5     = Punishing Barbs <br />ALT+6     = Shock Spikes <br />ALT+7     = Stygian Spikes <br />ALT+8     = Siphon MP <br />ALT+9     = Profundity <br />ALT+0     = Drain <br /> <br />---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- <br />10. <span style="color:deepskyblue">The Soloist vs The Party mage</span> <br /> <br /><u>Soloist Thaumaturge</u> <br /> <br />So far on my travels I have played solo (especially when I first started Alpha through to the beginning of Beta3). I have found as a solo mage there were some things I could do well and some things I could do really well!  <br /> <br />Spell Combinations: <br />Sacrifice&gt;Phantom Dart&gt;Damnation&gt;Punishing Barbs&gt;Slow&gt;Scourge/Banish <br />I would say at early levels (1-10) these are the best combinations I can find. PD and damnation are your bread and butter hitting spells that take JP off the mob and Sacrifice is the spell that saves you most of the time. Punishing Barbs is a great spell but you have to time it right. I only ever really use it as a soloist if the mobs is hitting harder than I first thought it would after I had engaged it, or, it is part a group/link set of mobs and want to do some damage to the others while I attack one target, or if I am faced with a powerful mob that builds up its TP to basically one shot me – this is useful on difficult leves because although you’ll die, as long as you have time you most likely will kill the mob with this spell and be ready by the time you get back to camp. I have never got any skill points off it when it was active so bear this in mind also. Slow is a fantastic spell for a solo THM, it slows down the mob to a crawl and most often sticks. This can really help you get a hit&gt;hit&gt;heal combination going and stay on top of the battle. Its timer can often last less than the cooldown, which is its only downfall. Scourge and Banish are a THM ‘s nukes and can hit for quite high numbers, I always have one set, if not both. <br /> <br />As you get higher in levels there are some very good spells for soloing such as Stygian Spikes – which can virtually mean you can nuke freely up to a point (especially since the exaltation timer has been decreased to ten minutes from 30).  Poison is a spell you get quite early on and I feel is underused as it is quite potent, usually sticks for a reasonable amount of time and doesn’t cost much mp, so its dmg/mp ratio is quite good. Blood Rite I have found recently to be a great addition as it really helps those spells get that little bit more damage.  Again a good one to set if you have the spare slots. <br /> <br />Now some spells have yet to prove themselves to me. Siphon MP can net you quite a lot of mp return if the mob is weak to magic or low enough, but often you will want to be fighting mobs that are at least decent prey because of the rank point rewards so I have found that having it set doesn’t outweigh the benefits of setting other spells in its place. If you are going to be a total nuker then maybe set with other spells this would be of benefit but unless you in a party it may not be worth it as stated. Bio and Dia, although have moderate benefits do not seem as potent in FFXIV as they were in FFXI, this is not to say that I don’t set them but they are only there if I have spare slots. Dark Seal is a spell that although it works well in getting a hit for a debuff etc as it only is there for one cast its 3 points is not really worth it at this stage. Maybe in the future when THM’s are higher in rank and fighting in large group it will prove invaluable. But for the solo mage its not a great spell. All of the Absorb spell have such a small amount of longevity it really doesn’t seem worth casting them and testing this spell with initiation and the fact that the party member receiving the benefit gets it for a very short time makes it redundant and obviously you would set initiation as a soloer anyway! <br /> <br /><u>Party Thaumaturge</u> <br />In my mind the Party THM is where the serious SP is at. You'll be fighting some amazing and tough mobs and I found this to be the most exciting and least repetitive (although I must admit to be getting sick of Efts).It is important to note that there is a big difference with a THM in a Battleleve and in an SP Party. <br /> <br />[Battleleves] <br />The Thaumaturge in a party is a difficult class to master at first. With the amount of emnity sacrifice and any debuff AoE's can generate you'll end up spending most of your shared-leves face down. With some careful playcraft you can eliminate this and mitigate any emnity (up to a point!). I find that using macro's is the key to being a party THM and keeping an eye on single target and aoe is essential. When in a battle situation make sure you tell any party members that they must wait for all buffs to be placed before they engage or else risk losing one of their team mates early on in the fray. Once engaged I found the tactic of initially waiting and then  hitting a few Phantom Darts to be a good way into the fight. Obviously as its a party the dynamics will depend on who you are with, what class they are and the party member total. Set AoE Sacrifice and when people look like they are around 50% hit it. By then you should be low on the hate list and will help out any CON that is trying to heal and nuke etc. Again in a party situation Slow is your freind and is still the debuff of choice (until you ge to higher levels of course). Don't forget that Stygian Spikes over write Shock Spikes so if you want to cast this at all (which you probably dont!) then make sure you do it away from the other players! One of the very popular techniques I have used as a party THM is Punishing Barbs - my team has won many a 5 star leve with me going in on a group of very tough mobs, everyone concentrating fire onto one mob and them getting hit with a large single damage hit which in turn reflects a considerable amount of damage back to the mob. On a dmg for dmg ratio you are looking at doing around 10X the damage of Scourge or Banish using this spell, and of course if you can survive that first hit then the second hit usually finishes off the mob for good. Expect to miss out on some rank points doing this though as you are constantly running back from the aetherlyte and cooling down your PB timer while your teamates might still be fighting and getting skill ups. Of course when you get the guildmarks its quite worthwhile to buy Silouette, as again you can deal out more damage to mobs and not get as much hate. At present it seems like us THM's are very good at emnity generation! I'm hopeing SE will fix this somehow in the future and allow us to at least aoe debuff if we desire. <br /> <br />[SP Party] <br /><s>I have found these non-leve fights much more like traditional party setups on FFXI (If you have played this you will know what I mean). Here you cast Sacrifice and Cure aoe to cure yourself (if needed) and the tank, which is very useful as most mobs are not a good idea to be in front of. I have partied with all of the classes and they all have their +/-'s. DOM classes can get equal skillups as our DOW counterparts but we have to be clever about it :) For example at 16-20 I was ranking up nearly two times faster than my team mates. I would say depending on the party you can expect an average of around 300SP per fight if you use the following methods and try and instruct your party in the ways of the mage: <br /> <br />1. Sacrifice 1 and Cure 1 only if more than 1 mage in party. Only use Tier II's if absolutely needed. <br />2. Stygian Spikes as often as you like (just remember that overwriting a buff <i>doesn't</i> net you SP!(ty Miayr) <br />3. Profundity + Scourge/Banish whenever its up - can net 250-300sp for just one successful hit. <br />4. Scourge/Banish when profundity is not up. <br />5. Siphon MP (not for SP gain but to keep MP up) when mob is dead (this gets you much more MP most of the time) <br />6. Spirit Dart/Phantom Dart when you get chance.(Again using Profundity here can get you a bigger hit and more SP) <br />7. Damnation/Radiance when you get the chance. <br />8. Protect and Shell during fight only if possible (does get you SP) - sometimes Protect is not needed though and can hurt SP! <br />9. ABS EVA can always be used but DEF/ACC can be situational depending on mob. I wouldnt recommend using ABS ATT because mob will hit people for less and it has no benifit for anyone on the team. <br />10. Dia not Bio (again depending on situation). Dia has chance of double proc similar to Scourge/Banish. <br />11. Any other debuffs you can manage that dont hurt your own SP gain - If you have time after all of the above! <br /> <br />Make sure that any other mages in your group understand these rules. <br />Make sure mele in your group dont use stun moves on mob, try to get them not to use anything that gives them HP back or DEF if you can!, and try to stop them using absorb/deplete TP moves as you want the mob to hit them with aoe! :) <br /> <br />I said previously 300SP per fight average, but if you hit the 'sweet spot' - being around the middle level in your party, not having many other mages and no Archers (sorry but you really gimp our SP) you can easily cap SP every fight.</s> <br /> <br />******** NOTE: This all became moot after the November 24th 2010 update! *********** <br /> <br />---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- <br />11. <span style="color:darkcyan">TESTING:</span> <br />Deleted Sction as this appears to have been fixed to some degree! <br />Any further ideas as always please post and I'll add and credit. <br /> <br />---------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- <br />12. Credits - Teneleven; Obiar; RhysOnKujata; Puppy; Miayr - -  Thank you guys :) <br /> <br />Updated Ability list - made easier to navigate with mouseovers. <br /> <br /> <br /><i><span class="sm">Edited, Dec  8th 2010  8:05pm by EdyNOTB </span></i> <br /> <br /><i><span class="sm">Edited, Dec  8th 2010  8:08pm by EdyNOTB </span></i> <br /> <br /><i><span class="sm">Edited, Dec  8th 2010  8:09pm by EdyNOTB </span></i><div class="msgSig"><div class="msgSigBar sm">----------------------------</div><a href="HTTP://lodestone.finalfantasyxiv.com/rc/character/status?cicuid=2993179" rel="external nofollow" title="lodestone.finalfantasyxiv.com/rc/character/status?cicuid=2993179">Loadstone Profile</a> <br /><a href="HTTP://ffxiv.zam.com/forum.html?forum=179&amp;mid=1282291867193441649" rel="external" title="ffxiv.zam.com/forum.html?forum=179&amp;mid=1282291867193441649">Thaumaturge Guide</a> <br /> <br /><img src="http://common.zam.com/xivsigs/1229110.png" alt="Signature Image" border="0" /> <br /></div></div>
